International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1] Madhya Pradesh State
Date: Thu, 6 Jul 2006 10:01:37 -0400 (EDT)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: India eNews.com, Gurgaon, Haryana, India, 6 Jul 2006 [edited]
<http://indiaenews.com/?s=chikungunya&sa>

Chikungunya, a relatively rare form of mosquito-transmitted viral fever,
has claimed 12 lives in Betul district of Madhya Pradesh, and the disease
has spread to 3 more districts.
With 3 more deaths Sunday -- 2 from remote Dunava and one from Multai --
the total number of deaths allegedly due to chikungunya fever in Betul
district has reached 12, a source in the medical fraternity here said Thursday.
Chikungunya, affecting over 60 000 odd people, is now spreading to other
districts -- Chhindwara, Badwani and Burhanpur. However, 70 blood samples
have been dispatched to the New Delhi-based National Institute of
Communicable Diseases and a report is expected next week, he added.
Chikungunya fever, which was first reported a month ago in the state,
reportedly entered Madhya Pradesh through villages in Betul district
bordering Maharashtra.
Health Minister Ajay Vishnoi admitted that Chhindwara, Badwani and
Burhanpur were affected with the fever. However, he said, "The situation is
under control and even the Maharashtra government has praised my
department's rapid action to tackle the disease."
On the deaths in Betul, he said: "It is yet to be confirmed whether they
were due to Chikungunya -- symptoms of which are quite similar to other
viral fevers."
--
